<br>
Fair warning....LOTS of quotes ahead (sorry <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Saddam was a &quot;friend of the west!&quot; once upon a time and his atrocities were mostly over looked.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But there wasn't much comment then...largely because he was seen as &quot;fighting the Iranians which was a Good Thing&quot;. Are you aware of that? The media bias due to government/economic reasons.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm very aware of that.  The US knew that he was using chemical weapons while he was using them, yet we moved to normalize trade relations with him.  Why?  Because it's what was in the best interest of the country at the time.  That's how politics works.  <br>
<br>
That was a very different time and the world was a very different place.  At that time Iran was seen as the major threat, not Iraq.<br>
<br>
The US and UK were allied with the Soviet Union and Joseph Stalin during WWII, as I'm sure you know.  Again, because it was in our best interests <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>at the time</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Doesn't necessarily make it a good thing, that's just the way it was.<br>
<br>
I don't know that there is really a media bias, I mean the information is readily available from major media outlets on the web.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And when did I ever say Saddam as a &quot;moderate&quot;? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You never said that he is a moderate in so many words.  But you did infer it...and I thought I made it pretty clear as to how you did so:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
...you know much about Islam? Sunni <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(moderate)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, Shiite (extremist), ok that's very simplistic but a rough idea of the two main factions...<br>
<br>
...Saddam and his allies are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Sunni</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> and secular...<br>
<br>
...And as far as I am aware, Baath or no Baath, his supporters are mostly Sunni muslims... <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Perhaps you can see where one could get confused.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I know rather well about Saddam's crimes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Look, I'm sure you do...I was just trying to put emphasis on a point.  So let's compromise and try not to stray any further in this direction than we already have.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...Saddam needs dealt with, but his COUNTRY does not need or should not be subjected to a WAR to get rid of a minority when the vast majority dont support him and will suffer (as wel as the costs to us in regards to personnel, relations and economics). Show me where I'm wrong, I like debate as you can learn a lot from it, but DONT say an out right lie...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why is it that you want so badly to believe that we are going to go in there and lay waste to the entire country through the judicious use of carpet bombing and napalm drops on entire cities so that we can take out one military target?  You <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>KNOW</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that is not how it happens.<br>
<br>
For christ's sake do I really have to explain to you how modern munitions work??  I know you know.  We can put them right in a window or down a chimney or through a door...<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>literally!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
You also like to use the premise that his &quot;country&quot;, which I take to mean his &quot;people&quot;, are our targets and our enemies.  That is simply not the case.  I do not know how to be any more plain about that.  The United States is not in the business of genocide...that is Saddam's territory.  I wish you'd get past the idea that we are as bad or worse than he is.<br>
